Dear Eric, dear Curt, dear..

first one remark on the makefiles.
In a private mail, Curt made the 
suggestion of perhaps trying to look for 
a better solution substiting the
different makefiles. I would 
support this idea prefering some sort
of Gnu autoconf or a similar tool.
Several years ago I remember my struggle 
with compiling SLIRP 
(full internet via ASCII terminal 
console, huh...). I had a lot of problems 
adapting the code to my HPUX or AIX at 
that time. After they changed to autoconf 
all went very smoothly. I remember it 
checked automatically the libraries installed, 
the Unix version etc.
If I recall right ACM has a similar
routine. Don't know if it's general enough
to cover all the systems we want to include,
though.

Of course there's nothing for free:
I think, however, it's simpler
to switch to this procedure at the very 
beginning and debugging this one with 
only few code than doing it later.

On another point:
Eric pointed out that his win32
version (For me still unclear
how to build natively under win95) 
is substantially slower than, for instance, 
the OS/2 version. I can well imagine this.
Pure windows (incl.95) is always slow.
Wouldn't it be appropriate for a graphics intense
project as this to make use of the DirectX API?
(Nearly) all commercial win95 game developers
make use of this. The corresponding SDK is freely 
available from MS, although I don't know how 
difficult it's to use.

The runtime libraries of the most recent version
directX3 available from

http://www.microsoft.com/gamesdev/gsdk/directx.zip

are "only" 6MB (freely available from MS
as well). The development kit at

http://www.microsoft.com/msdownload/directx3.htm

is araund 80MB(!), if I recall right.
Includes 'some' documentation.
To my best knowedge (as a non-developer) this is
the de-facto standard in win95 games programming
(including Fs95). The point is, that it leaves only
a very thin layer between your code and the hardware.
If I recall right, it even works on NT4.0.

Greetings Michael Basler (pmb@rz.uni-jena.de)
