to a command-line interface (which is not a problem 
for TeX being command-line oriented) and unable to
run any graphics. Perhaps not a good starting point
for a flight simulator...

Next: I think you can do win32 programming under
win3.1/win32s. However, there are some essential
differences and you will miss several points,
one of the most important one being the use of the
registry database and, as you mentioned, directX
support. You can of course do some stuff this way,
but for a professional program (flight gear
should be one, shouldn't it) I would prefer a 
native win95/winnt4.0 program using the registry,
the win95 installation procedure etc. If you 
find a machine to have a look on  Pascal 
Meziats recently released Airport 2.0
which is win95/nt4.0 and which is free,
you will see what I mean.

I heared that Matt Pickering (address on the
Flight gear home page, perhaps you can find a 
way to co-ordiante your work) is already working on
the win 95 stuff using the Borland compiler, too.
(If I recall right.) From my point of view (as
a non-developer) this idea might not be too
good as a long-term solution for a (free) GNU
project. I would really prefer working with 
free stuff only (maybe up to the OS, 
but we have Linux...)

