> Since you will be developing Multiplayer Internet support an ATC client
> should be on your list of to do's.  I would certainly volunteer for such a
> project and would only need the specs for the server.

We can certainly use all the help I can get.  If you haven't joined
the mailing list yet, please do so by sending mail to majordomo@infoplane.com
with a message body of "subscribe flight-gear"

ATC hasn't been discussed in a while, so I'm unsure if anyone has made up
any specs for this.  I'm not really sure if the ATC support should be
considered a client or a server. :)  It would be great to have designated
ATC servers providing positive control (where required) either automatically
from the server, or manually by someone connected to the ATC server via
a client.  The ATC server could also provide dynamic scenery (regularly 
scheduled flights).  I sort of envision connetions and messages like....

** server = ATC/dynamic scenery server
** Flight Gear client = flight gear program
** ATC client = ATC client
** client = either flight gear or ATC client

server->Flight Gear client: Interrogate Transponder
Flight Gear client->server: (if transponder on and in range return 
		                  pos,vel,transponder code)

client->server: Request nearby traffic (pos,radius)
ATC Server->Flight Gear client: (list of nearby traffic pos,vel,code)

client->server: register com frequency (flags VOICE,TEXT,BOTH)
server->client: (acknowledge) add to list of clients on frequency

client->server: unregister com frequency
server->client: (acknowledge) remove from list of clients on frequency

client->server: text message on frequency
server->client: (acknowledge) send message to all in range on frequency

client->server: voice message on frequency
server->client: (acknowledge) send message to all in range on frequency

ATC client->server: Become controller for sector
server->ATC client: (Acknowledge yes or no.)

server->servers for ajacent sectors: handoffs, etc.

This is a beginning, so it is undoubtably incomplete.  The exact format of the
message and which TCP ports are to be used is up to the developers.  I'd
hope to keep the message sizes to a minimum (which is hard to do on voice).
For now ATC commands would have to be text.  (It would be hard for the
server to change voice into a command for dynamic scenery.)  I'm sending
this to the mailing list so others that are interested can help you
develop a spec and protocols. 

